The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN), on Friday, made interventions in the Retail Secondary Market Intervention Sales (SMIS) of the Foreign Exchange market totaling $271.83 million and CNY41.14m. The Director, Corporate Communications at the CBN, Mr. Isaac Okorafor, also confirmed that CNY41.14m was for payment of Renminbi-denominated Letters of Credit for agriculture, as well as raw materials. Friday’s transaction was in addition to the $205m injected into the Wholesale, Small and Medium Enterprises, and Invisibles segments of the market on Tuesday, April 30, 2019. Mr. Okorafor expressed satisfaction with the performance and stability of the country’s economy, noting that the country would experience more growth as the bank had placed restrictions on the purchase of forex from the Nigerian foreign exchange market for items in the textile and cotton value chain. Meanwhile, the naira exchanged at N360/$1 on Friday, May 3, 2019, in the Bureau De Change (BDC) segment of the market.  Forex: CBN injects $268.4m, CNY46.3m into retail SMIS Forex: Again, CBN intervenes with $268.60m, CNY39.09m Forex: CBN injects $303m, CNY46.58m into market Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin